Real Madrid beat Espanyol 3-0 to
move atop Spanish soccerâ€™s La Liga and extend its 100 percent
home record under coach Jose Mourinho.  Cristiano Ronaldo  opened the scoring in the 28th minute
last night before  Gonzalo Higuain  and  Karim Benzema  got their
first goals of the season. Espanyol finished the game with nine
men after Ernesto Galan and Juan Forlin were red-carded.  Real leads the standings with 10 points from four games,
ahead of Valencia on nine points. Sevilla and Athletic Bilbao,
which beat Real Mallorca 3-0 last night, have seven points.  Osasuna was a 3-1 winner over Real Sociedad in the other
match. Defending champion Barcelona, which is in seventh place,
hosts Sporting Gijon today.  In Germany, Mainz opened up a five-point lead atop the
Bundesliga with a 2-0 win over Cologne.  Lewis Holtby scored both goals as Mainz made it five wins
in as many games. Second-place Hoffenheim was beaten 2-1 at home
by defending champion Bayern Munich.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
